.TH ZC 1 "January 2026" "Zen-C 0.1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
zc \- Zen\-C transpiler and compiler
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B zc
[\fB\-h\fR|\fB\-\-help\fR]
[\fB\-v\fR|\fB\-\-version\fR]
[\fICOMMAND\fR]
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
[\fIFILE\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B zc
is a transpiler that converts Zen\-C code to standard C code and optionally compiles it. 
Zen\-C allows you to write code with modern high\-level language features while maintaining 
C's performance and low\-level control. The transpiler outputs clean, readable C code that 
can be compiled with any standard C compiler (GCC, Clang, Zig, TCC).
.PP
Zen\-C provides:
.IP \(bu 2
Type inference and generic programming
.IP \(bu 2
Pattern matching with \fBmatch\fR expressions
.IP \(bu 2
Growable vectors (zvec.h) with automatic memory management
.IP \(bu 2
UTF\-8 strings (zstr.h) with 22\-byte short string optimization
.IP \(bu 2
Doubly\-linked lists (zlist.h) with O(1) operations
.IP \(bu 2
Hash maps (zmap.h) with open addressing and linear probing
.IP \(bu 2
Traits and interfaces
.IP \(bu 2
Async/await support
.IP \(bu 2
Manual memory management with RAII patterns
.IP \(bu 2
Single\-header library architecture
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B build
Transpile Zen\-C source to C code and compile to executable
.TP
.B run
Transpile, compile and immediately execute the program
.TP
.B transpile
Convert Zen\-C source to C code without compiling
.TP
.B test
Run the test suite
.TP
.B clean
Remove generated files and build artifacts
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Display help information and exit
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-version
Display version information and exit
.TP
.BR \-\-cc " " \fICOMPILER\fR
Specify C compiler to use: \fBgcc\fR (default), \fBclang\fR, \fBzig\fR, or \fBtcc\fR
.TP
.BR \-\-std " " \fISTANDARD\fR
Specify C standard version (e.g., c99, c11, c17, c23)
.TP
.BR \-O [ 0 | 1 | 2 | 3 | s ]
Set optimization level for compilation
.TP
.BR \-g
Generate debug information
.TP
.BR \-o " " \fIFILE\fR
Specify output file name
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Transpile and run a Zen\-C program:
.PP
.RS
.nf
zc run hello.zc
.fi
.RE
.PP
Build an executable with GCC:
.PP
.RS
.nf
zc build \-\-cc gcc \-O2 program.zc
.fi
.RE
.PP
Transpile to C code only:
.PP
.RS
.nf
zc transpile source.zc \-o output.c
.fi
.RE
.PP
Build with Clang and optimization:
.PP
.RS
.nf
zc build \-\-cc clang \-O3 \-o myapp app.zc
.fi
.RE
.PP
Run tests with specific compiler:
.PP
.RS
.nf
zc test \-\-cc zig
.fi
.RE
.SH LANGUAGE FEATURES
.SS Type Inference
Variables can be declared without explicit types using type inference:
.PP
.RS
.nf
let x = 42;          // inferred as int
let msg = "Hello";   // inferred as string
let items = Vec.new();  // generic vector
.fi
.RE
.SS Pattern Matching
Zen\-C supports powerful pattern matching with the \fBmatch\fR expression:
.PP
.RS
.nf
match value {
    0 => print("zero"),
    1..=10 => print("one to ten"),
    _ => print("other")
}
.fi
.RE
.SS Vectors
Dynamic arrays with automatic memory management:
.PP
.RS
.nf
Vec<int> numbers = Vec.new();
Vec.push(&numbers, 42);
Vec.push(&numbers, 100);
int value = Vec.pop(&numbers);
.fi
.RE
.SS Strings
UTF\-8 string support with views and formatting:
.PP
.RS
.nf
String s = Str.new("Hello");
Str.append(&s, " World");
StrView view = Str.view(&s);
.fi
.RE
.SS Lists
Non\-intrusive doubly\-linked lists:
.PP
.RS
.nf
List<int> list = List.new();
List.push_back(&list, 10);
List.push_front(&list, 5);
.fi
.RE
.SS Hash Maps
Open\-addressing hash tables with type safety:
.PP
.RS
.nf
Map<String, int> ages = Map.new();
Map.insert(&ages, "Alice", 30);
int* age = Map.get(&ages, "Alice");
.fi
.RE
